Trust me, Government asks that we concentrate our hopes and dreams on one man, that we trust him to do what's best for us.

50
00:08:20.101 --> 00:08:29.900
For my view of government places trust not in one person or one party, but in those values that transcend persons and parties.

51
00:08:30.601 --> 00:08:44.800
The trust is where it belongs in the people.

52
00:08:45.401 --> 00:08:50.500
The responsibility to live up to that trust is where it belongs in their elected leaders.

53
00:08:51.201 --> 00:08:56.100
That kind of relationship between the people and their elected leaders is a special kind of compact.

54
00:08:56.801 --> 00:09:05.700
360 years ago, in 1620, a group of families dared to cross a mighty ocean to build a future for themselves in a new world.

55
00:09:06.701 --> 00:09:16.700
When they arrived at Plymouth, MA, they formed what they called a compact, an agreement among themselves to build a community and abide by its laws.

56
00:09:17.401 --> 00:09:25.600
This single act, the voluntary binding together of free people to live under the law, set the pattern for what was to come.

57
00:09:26.701 --> 00:09:35.200
A century and a half later, the descendants of those people pledged their lives, their fortunes, and their sacred honor to found this nation.

58
00:09:36.001 --> 00:09:39.100
Some forfeited their fortunes and their lives.

59
00:09:39.801 --> 00:10:05.600
None sacrificed honor, 4 score and seven years later, Abraham Lincoln called upon the people of all America to renew their dedication and their commitment to a government of, for and by the people.

60
00:10:06.401 --> 00:10:21.500
Isn't it once again time to renew our compact of freedom, to pledge to each other, to pledge to each other all that is best in our lives, all that gives meaning to them.

61
00:10:21.701 --> 00:10:28.600
For the sake of this, our beloved and blessed land together, let us make this a new beginning.

62
00:10:29.301 --> 00:10:42.900
Let us make a commitment to care for the needy, to teach our children the virtues handed down to us by our families, to have the courage to defend those values and virtues of the willingness to sacrifice for them.

63
00:10:43.601 --> 00:10:57.300
Let us pledge to restore in our time the American spirit of voluntary service, of cooperation, of private and community initiative, a spirit that flows like a deep and mighty river through the history of our nation.

64
00:10:58.301 --> 00:11:08.400
As your nominee, I pledge to you to restore to the federal government the capacity to do the people's work without dominating their lives.

65
00:11:09.101 --> 00:11:41.200
I pledge to you, I pledge to you a government that will not only work well, but wisely, its ability to act tempered by prudence and its willingness to do good, balanced by the knowledge that government is never more dangerous, that when our desire to have it help us blinds us to its great power to harm us.

66
00:11:50.701 --> 00:12:09.500
