178
00:32:41.801 --> 00:32:50.100
You know there may be a sailor at the helm of the ship of state, but the ship has no rudder.

179
00:32:52.301 --> 00:32:58.600
Critical, Critical decisions are made, at times almost in comic fashion.

180
00:32:58.801 --> 00:32:59.800
But who can laugh?

181
00:33:00.401 --> 00:33:20.800
Who was not embarrassed when the administration handed a major propaganda victory in the United Nations to the enemies of Israel, our staunch Middle East ally, for three decades, and then claimed that the American vote was a mistake, the result of a failure of communication between the president, his Secretary of State, and his UN ambassador?

182
00:33:21.601 --> 00:33:37.900
Who does not feel a growing sense of unease as our allies, facing repeated instances of an amateuration can and confused administration, reluctantly conclude that America is unwilling or unable to fulfill its obligations as leader of the free world?

183
00:33:38.601 --> 00:33:46.200
Who does not feel rising alarm when the question and any discussion of foreign policy is no longer Should we do something?

184
00:33:46.801 --> 00:33:50.000
But do we have the capacity to do anything?

185
00:33:58.801 --> 00:34:08.600
The administration which has brought us to this state is seeking your endorsement for four more years of weakness, indecision, mediocrity and incompetence.

186
00:34:09.401 --> 00:34:16.199
No, no, no American should vote until he or she has asked.

187
00:34:16.700 --> 00:34:21.900
Is the United States stronger and more respected now than it was 3 1/2 years ago?

188
00:34:24.301 --> 00:34:27.800
Is the world safer, a safer place in which to live?

189
00:34:28.601 --> 00:34:41.600
It is the reason it is the responsibility of the President of the United States in working for peace to ensure that the safety of our people cannot successfully be threatened by a hostile foreign power.

190
00:34:42.401 --> 00:34:48.300
As President, fulfilling that responsibility will be my number one priority.

191
00:35:03.501 --> 00:35:05.000
We're not a war like people.

192
00:35:05.601 --> 00:35:06.700
Quite the opposite.

193
00:35:07.501 --> 00:35:09.400
We always seek to live in peace.

194
00:35:09.901 --> 00:35:17.000
We resort to force infrequently and with great reluctance, and only after we've determined that it's absolutely necessary.

195
00:35:17.901 --> 00:35:23.800
We are awed, and rightly so, by the forces of destruction that loosen the world in its nuclear era.

196
00:35:25.001 --> 00:35:27.300
But neither can we be naive or foolish.

197
00:35:28.301 --> 00:35:42.300
4 times in my lifetime America has gone to war, bleeding the lives of its young men into the sands of island beachheads, the fields of Europe, and the jungles and rice paddies of Asia.

198
00:35:43.201 --> 00:35:50.100
We know only too well that war comes not when the forces of freedom are strong, it is when they are weak.

199
00:35:50.601 --> 00:35:52.000
The tyrants are tempted.

200
00:35:52.501 --> 00:36:26.100
We simply cannot learn these lessons the hard way again without risking our destruction of of all of all of all the objectives we seek.

201
00:36:26.601 --> 00:36:31.900
First and foremost is the establishment of lasting World Peace.

202
00:36:32.601 --> 00:36:38.500
We must always stand ready to negotiate in good faith, ready to pursue any reasonable Ave.

203
00:36:38.501 --> 00:36:43.300
that holds forth the promise of lessening tensions and furthering the prospects of peace.

204
00:36:44.001 --> 00:36:47.400
But let our friends and those who may wish us.

205
00:36:47.401 --> 00:36:48.400
I'll take note.

206
00:36:49.301 --> 00:37:01.800
The United States has an obligation to its citizens and to the people of the world never to let those who would destroy freedom dictate the future course of life on this planet.

207
00:37:13.801 --> 00:37:25.800
I would regard, I would regard my election as proof that we have renewed our resolve to preserve World Peace and freedom, that this nation will once again be strong enough to do that.

208
00:37:27.201 --> 00:37:43.100
Now, this evening, this evening marks the last steps save one of a campaign that has taken Nancy and me from one end of this great nation to the other over many months and thousands and thousands of miles.

209
00:37:43.901 --> 00:37:53.100
There are those who question the way we choose a president, who say that our process imposes difficult and exhausting burdens on those who seek the office.

210
00:37:54.201 --> 00:37:55.200
I have not found it.

211
00:37:55.201 --> 00:37:57.700
So it is.

212
00:38:02.101 --> 00:38:02.600
It is.

213
00:38:04.401 --> 00:38:13.000
It's impossible to capture in words the splendor of this vast continent, which God has granted as our portion of His creation.

214
00:38:13.801 --> 00:38:26.900
There are no words to express the extraordinary strength and character of this breed of people we call American everywhere, Everywhere.

215
00:38:26.901 --> 00:38:41.400
We've met thousands of Democrats, independents and Republicans from all economic conditions, all walks of life, bound together in that community of shared values of family, work, neighborhood, peace and freedom.

216
00:38:42.001 --> 00:38:43.600
They are concerned, yes.

217
00:38:44.101 --> 00:38:45.000
They're not frightened.

218
00:38:45.801 --> 00:38:48.200
They're disturbed, but not dismayed.

219
00:38:49.001 --> 00:38:57.100
They are the kind of men and women Tom Paine had in mind when he wrote during the darkest days of the American Revolution.

220
00:38:58.201 --> 00:39:03.000
We have it in our power to begin the world over again.

221
00:39:14.101 --> 00:39:26.700
Nearly nearly 150 years after Tom Paine wrote those words, an American president told the generation of the Great Depression that it had a rendezvous with destiny.

222
00:39:27.701 --> 00:39:36.300
I believe this generation of Americans today also has a rendezvous with destiny tonight.

223
00:39:40.401 --> 00:39:45.100
Tonight, let us dedicate ourselves to renewing the American compact.

224
00:39:45.701 --> 00:39:55.700
I ask you not simply to trust me, but to trust your values, our values, and to hold me responsible for living up to them.

225
00:39:56.501 --> 00:40:05.900
I ask you to trust that American spirit, which knows no ethnic, religious, social, political, regional or economic boundaries.

226
00:40:06.501 --> 00:40:13.100
The spirit that burned with zeal in the hearts of millions of immigrants from every corner of the earth who came here in search of freedom.

227
00:40:14.001 --> 00:40:17.800
Some say that spirit no longer exists, but I've seen it.

228
00:40:18.501 --> 00:40:25.000
I felt it all across this land, in the big cities, the small towns, and in rural America.

229
00:40:25.401 --> 00:40:32.600
It's still there, ready to blaze into life if you and I are willing to do what has to be done.

230
00:40:42.001 --> 00:40:52.500
We we have to do the practical things, the down to earth things such as creating policies that will stimulate our economy, increase productivity, and put America back to work.

231
00:40:53.201 --> 00:41:02.100
The time is now to limit federal spending, to insist on a stable monetary reform, and to free ourselves from imported oil.

232
00:41:02.801 --> 00:41:03.600
The time.

233
00:41:10.501 --> 00:41:26.400
The time is now to resolve that the basis of a firm and principled foreign policy is one that takes the world as it is and seeks to change it by leadership and example, not by harangue, harassment or wishful thinking.

234
00:41:27.301 --> 00:41:29.000
The time now is now.

235
00:41:32.101 --> 00:41:45.100
The time is now to say that we shall seek new friendships and expand others and improve others, but we shall not do so by breaking our word or casting aside old friends and allies.

236
00:41:55.001 --> 00:42:07.500
And the time is now to redeem promises once made to the American people by another candidate in another time and another place, he said.

237
00:42:08.701 --> 00:42:17.200
For three long years I have been going up and down this country preaching that government, Federal, state and local cost too much.

238
00:42:17.701 --> 00:42:22.000
I shall not stop that preaching as an immediate program of action.

239
00:42:22.001 --> 00:42:24.900
We must abolish useful, useless offices.

240
00:42:25.201 --> 00:42:28.400
We must eliminate unnecessary functions of government.

241
00:42:29.001 --> 00:42:37.100
We must consolidate subdivisions of government and like the private citizen, give up luxuries which we can no longer afford.

242
00:42:37.701 --> 00:42:51.400
And then he said, I propose to you, my friends, and through you, that government of all kinds, big and little, be made solvent, and that the example be set by the president of the United States and his cabinet.

243
00:42:52.001 --> 00:42:52.800
End of quote.

244
00:42:54.701 --> 00:43:02.600
That was Franklin Delano Roosevelt's words as he accepted the Democratic nomination for president in 1932.

245
00:43:03.701 --> 00:43:13.200
The time, the time is now, my fellow Americans, to recapture our destiny, to take it into our own hands.

246
00:43:14.101 --> 00:43:19.100
And to do this will take away many of us or will take many of us working together.

247
00:43:19.601 --> 00:43:28.500
I ask you tonight all over this land to volunteer your help in this cause so that we can carry our message throughout the land.

248
00:43:29.801 --> 00:43:48.400
Isn't it time that we the people carry out those unkept promises that we pledge to each other and to all America on this July day, 48 years later, that now we intend to do just that?

249
00:44:00.701 --> 00:44:11.600
I I have, I have thought of something that's not a part of my speech and worried over whether I should do it.

250
00:44:12.901 --> 00:44:20.700
Can we doubt that only a divine Providence placed this land, this island of freedom?

251
00:44:21.301 --> 00:44:26.000
Here is a refuge for all those people in the world who yearn to breathe free.

252
00:44:27.301 --> 00:44:31.400
Jews and Christians enduring persecution behind the Iron Curtain.

253
00:44:32.401 --> 00:44:35.800
The boat people of Southeast Asia, of Cuba and of Haiti.

254
00:44:37.001 --> 00:44:45.500
The victims of drought and famine in Africa, the freedom fighters in Afghanistan, and our own countrymen held in savage captivity.

255
00:44:47.701 --> 00:44:53.100
I'll confess that I've been a little afraid to suggest what I'm going to suggest.

256
00:44:56.401 --> 00:44:58.000
I'm more afraid not to.

257
00:45:00.001 --> 00:45:01.800
Can we begin our crusade?

258
00:45:03.201 --> 00:45:06.500
Join together in a moment of silent prayer.

259
00:45:19.701 --> 00:45:21.000
God Bless America.

260
00:45:22.301 --> 00:45:22.700
Thank you.